06489nam a22007935i 9780773596290DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735962907 a10.1515/97807735962902doi  a(DE-B1597)655518  a(OCoLC)1259191929  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJS1711b.C26 2014 7aPOL0020002bisacsh04a307.7609712231 aGraham, Katherine A.H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCanada in Cities :bThe Politics and Policy of Federal-Local Governance /cCaroline Andrew, Katherine A.H. Graham. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFields of Governance: Policy Making in Canadian Municipalities ;v700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tThe Federal “Communities Agenda”: Metagovernance for Place-based Policy in Canada? -- tReforming the Multilevel Governance of Emergencies: Municipalities and the Discursive Politics of Canada's Emergency Management Policy -- tHomelessness on the Federal Agenda: Progressive Architecture but No Solution in Sight -- tThe Federal Gas Tax Cession: From Advocacy Efforts to Thirteen Signed Agreements -- tInstitutional Arrangements and Planning Outcomes: Inter-agency Competition on the Toronto Waterfront -- tTracking the Growth of the Federal Municipal Infrastructure Program under Different Political Regimes -- tCities and Child Care Policy in Canada: More than a Puppet on (Intergovernmental) Strings? -- tFederal Policies on Immigrant Settlement -- tFederal Urban Aboriginal Policy: The Challenge of Viewing the Stars in the Urban Night Sky -- tConclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe federal government and its policies transform Canadian cities in myriad ways. Canada in Cities examines this relationship to better understand the interplay among changing demographics, how local governments and citizens frame their arguments for federal action, and the ways in which the national government uses its power and resources to shape urban Canada. Most studies of local governance in Canada focus on politics and policy within cities. The essays in this collection turn such analysis on its head, by examining federal programs, rather than municipal ones, and observing how they influence local policies and work with regional authorities and civil societies. Through a series of case studies - ranging from federal policy concerning Aboriginal people in cities, to the introduction of the federal gas tax transfer to municipalities, to the impact of Canada's emergency management policies on cities - the contributors provide insights about how federal politics influence the local political arena. Analyzing federal actions in diverse policy fields, the authors uncover meaningful patterns of federal action and outcome in Canadian cities. A timely contribution, Canada in Cities offers a comprehensive study of diverse areas of municipal public policy that have emerged in Canada in recent years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCities and towns -- Canada -- Case studies. 0aCities and townszCanadavCase studies. 0aFederal-city relations -- Canada -- Case studies. 0aFederal-city relationszCanadavCase studies. 0aMunicipal government -- Canada -- Case studies. 0aMunicipal governmentzCanadavCase studies. 0aUrban policy -- Canada -- Case studies. 0aUrban policyzCanadavCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aAbdourhamane Hima, Rachida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat